'''Distonic ions''' are [[Chemical substance|chemical]] species that contain 2 ionic charges on the same [[molecule]]. The charges must be separated by two or more carbon or hetero atoms to count as distonic (distant). Otherwise it is a gitonic (close) ion. For example, the acid-catalyzed [[Grewe-cyclization]] is a well-known reaction based on formation of a distonic ion, initiating the ring closing step as a superelectrophile.<ref name=Douglas2008>{{Cite book | last = Olah | first = George A. | year = 2008| title = Superelectrophiles and their chemistry | publisher = Willey-Interscience | pages = 287 |isbn=978-0-470-18511-7}}</ref> Distonic radical ions were first discovered in the [[gas]] [[Phase (matter)|phase]] by [[Michael L. Gross (chemist)|Michael L. Gross]].<ref name=Holman1986>{{Cite journal | last = Holman | first = R. | year = 1986 | title = Mass spectrometry for investigations of gas-phase radical cation chemistry the two step cycloaddition of the benzene radical cation and 1,3-butadiene | journal = Tetrahedron | volume = 42 | pages = 6235–6244 | doi = 10.1016/S0040-4020(01)88085-6 | issue = 22}}</ref> In recent years there has been a tremendous effort to identify new distonic species, characterize their [[reactivity (chemistry)|reactivity]], and measure their stability.<ref name="pmid">{{cite journal |vauthors=Tomazela DM, Sabino AA, Sparrapan R, Gozzo FC, Eberlin MN |title=Distonoid ions |journal=J. Am. Soc. Mass Spectrom. |volume=17 |issue=7 |pages=1014–22 |date=July 2006|doi=10.1016/j.jasms.2006.03.008 |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1044-0305(06)00271-6 |pmid=16713292}}</ref><ref name="pmid17286357">{{cite journal |vauthors=Ibrahim Y, Mabrouki R, Meot-Ner M, El-Shall MS |title=Hydrogen bonding interactions of pyridine*+ with water: stepwise solvation of distonic cations |journal=J Phys Chem A |volume=111 |issue=6 |pages=1006–14 |date=February 2007 |pmid=17286357 |doi=10.1021/jp067390h|bibcode=2007JPCA..111.1006I }}</ref><ref name="pmid17200931">{{cite journal |vauthors=Bouchoux G, Berruyer F, Hiberty PC, Wu W |title=Classical and distonic radical cations: a valence bond approach |journal=Chemistry |volume=13 |issue=10 |pages=2912–9 |year=2007 |pmid=17200931 |doi=10.1002/chem.200600985 |url=}}</ref>
