{{Orphan|date=September 2018}}
'''Echigo-jofu''' ({{nihongo|越後上布}}) is a fabric of [[Echigo]], Japan on national [[Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Properties]] listing in 1955,<ref name=tobunken/><ref name=Google/> and UNESCO's [[Intangible cultural heritage|Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity]] list since 2009.<ref name=UNESCO/> It is made from fine [[bast fiber]] from the [[ramie]] plant (''Boehmeria nivea''), also called hemp, although not directly related to ''cannabis'' hemp.{{efn|See ''Morphological Differences Between Ramie and Hemp: How These Characteristics Developed Different Procedures in Bast Fiber Producing Industry'';<ref name=Hwang2010/> also see [[:wikt:麻布]]}} After it is woven on a ''jibata'' [[backstrap loom]] ({{nihongo|地機}}), the fabric is spread on snowfields (''yuki-zarashi'') where ultraviolet light from the sun creates ozone and bleaches it white.<ref name=IHCSA/><ref name=Yamada/> The fabric is used to make summer [[kimonos]] and other traditional garments, cushions and bed linens.<ref>{{citation|title=Dyeing & weaving – Echigo jofu, ojiya chijimi|publisher=Cultural foundation for promoting the national costume of Japan |url=http://www.kimono.or.jp/dictionary/eng/echigojoufu.html}}</ref>
