The '''Machar Marshes''' are a large area of wetlands in the state of [[Upper Nile (state)|Upper Nile]], [[South Sudan]].  Estimates of their size vary. A 1950 study put the area of swamp at 6,500&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.<ref>Sutcliffe and Parks, p.107</ref>  A 1980 study put the area of permanent swamp at 8,700&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>., 60% of which was grass and forest.<ref>Sutcliffe and Parks, p.113</ref>

The marshes are fed by waters from the Khor Machar (a distributary of the [[Baro River]]), the [[Yabus River]] and the [[Daga River (South Sudan)|Daga River]].  At times of high water they are also fed by spill from the [[Pibor River]].  The marshes are drained by the [[Adar River]], a tributary of the [[White Nile]].

